04633nam a22006975i 9780691188621DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182002nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911886217 a10.1515/97806911886212doi  a(DE-B1597)501782  a(OCoLC)1076445566  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHN690.B6bH36 2001eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a306/.0954/79232231 aHansen, Thomas Blom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWages of Violence :bNaming and Identity in Postcolonial Bombay /cThomas Blom Hansen. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcronyms -- tIntroduction: The Proper Name -- tChapter 1. Deccan Pastoral: The Making of an Ethnohistorical Imagination in Western India -- tChapter 2. Bombay and the Politics of Urban Desire -- tChapter 3. "Say with Pride That We Are Hindus": Shiv Sena and Communal Populism -- tChapter 4. Thane City: The Making of Political Dadaism -- tChapter 5. Riots, Policing, and Truth Telling in Bombay -- tChapter 6. In the Muslim Mohalla -- tChapter 7. Living the Dream: Governance, Graft, and Goons -- tConclusion. Politics as Permanent Performance -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Bombay changed its name to Mumbai in 1995, it was the culmination of a long process that transformed India's primary symbol of modernity and cultural diversity into a site of intense ethnic conflict and violent nationalism. Wages of Violence is a startling account of how the city's atmosphere, dominant public languages, and power structures have changed since the 1960s. The book centers on how Shiv Sena, a militant Hindu movement, has advanced a new, ''plebeian'' political culture and has undermined democratic rule in India's premier city. Drawing on a large body of archival material and conversations with people from all walks of life, Thomas Blom Hansen paints a vivid picture of this dynamic and violent movement. Challenging conventional views of recent trends in Indian politics, Hansen shows that the xenophobic public culture of today's Mumbai has deep roots in the region's history and its contested identities. We are also given revealing insights into the city's Muslim communities and the authorities' understanding and control of the ethno-religious subcultures in the city. Hansen argues cogently that Shiv Sena's success represents the violent possibilities of the ''vernacularization'' of democracy in India. Unfolding at a juncture where the globalization of India's economy is having a deepening impact on the lives of ordinary people, this is a story that resonates with the directions urban growth is taking both elsewhere in India and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndiaxPolitics And Governmentx20Th Century. 0aIndiaxSocial Conditions. 0aMumbai (India). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188621zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691188621423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188621.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK